abstract = {To investigate the sequence dependence in the molecular mechanism of$\backslash$nurea induced denaturation, molecular dynamics denaturing simulations of$\backslash$ntwo beta-hairpin peptides, a fast folding peptide 1 (SESYINPDGTWTVTE)$\backslash$nand a slow folding TRPZIP4 (GEWTWDDATKTWTWTE), were performed in urea$\backslash$naqueous solutions. It was found that beta-hairpin denaturation by urea$\backslash$nis highly dependent on the hydrophobicity of the side chains. The two$\backslash$nbeta-hairpin peptides studied here and the GB1 studied previously$\backslash$ndisplay three different denaturant processes in urea solution by which$\backslash$nthe breaking of backbone native hydrogen bonds takes different orders.$\backslash$nThe variation of their denaturing mechanism is well correlated to the$\backslash$nvariation in their structural properties. In peptide 1, which has only a$\backslash$nloosely packed hydrophobic core formed by residues Trp11 and Ile5, all$\backslash$nbackbone native hydrogen bonds (1 to 5) are broken in a short period of$\backslash$ntime. Whereas for TRPZIP4 with a compact hydrophobic core of four$\backslash$ntryptophan residues, the backbone native hydrogen bonds (1 to 6) are$\backslash$nconsiderably more stable, with the middle hydrogen bonds protected well$\backslash$nby the hydrophobic core being the most stable. The comparison of$\backslash$ndifferent beta-hairpin peptides shows that the side-chain packing on$\backslash$neach face of the strands plays a major role in the stability of the$\backslash$nbackbone native hydrogen bonds in urea solution, and indicates that$\backslash$nprotein denaturation by urea can be highly sequence dependent.},
